	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0381">381<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0381.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div class="doc">

<h1>From C. W. F. Dumas</h1>
<div class="docbody" xml:lang="fra">
<div class="opener"><table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Monsieur</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">LaHaie 3<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> Avril 1783</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Nous savons ici, par Lettres de Hambourg du 25 du pass, que Mr. Votre fils, aprs Sy tre arrt quelques jours, en toit reparti le 23.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
   <p>Voici des Lettres Amricaines venues par la poste dAngleterre. Celle de Mr. Guild Sest trouve dans un paquet entierement us &amp; <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0382">[382<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0382.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span> <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0383">[383<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0383.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span><span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0384">[384<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0384.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>ouvert dun ct. Il contenoit deux brochures: <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Letter to the Abb Raynal by Th<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">s.</span> Payne</span>, &amp; <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Catalogus eorum qui in Universitate Harvardiana Cantabrigi in Rep. Massach<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">si.</span> ab ao 1642 ad an. 1782 alicujus gradus laurea donati sunt.</span><a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> Jai cru devoir dposer ces deux pieces dans votre Secretaire, &amp; vous envoyer Seulement la Lettre.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0003" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>A certain face you would not meet in a wood, you will meet it, with his influenza in the future Congress of final pacification, at which I am assured he is appointed to assist. I Sat next him yesterday at the F. Ambassadors, who gave a Diplomatic Dinner.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0004" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> We were much talkative together about the several climates of Russia nearly corresponding with those of our States, and the extensiveness of both, about Kamtschatka, Capt. Cook, the Caspian Sea and Mount Caucase, which he told me he went through. There, said I, you may possibly have traaden on some of the Steps of Alexander the great. He Smiled, and I too, fancying him horded, when there, with the modern Hircanians, so formidable to Caravans.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0005" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0005-ptr">5</a></p>
<p>Je Suis avec grand respect, De Votre Exc<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> / le trs-humble &amp; trs / obissant serviteur</p>
<div class="closer"><p class="signed">Dumas</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="translation">
<h2><span class="hi-all-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps; text-transform: lowercase;">Translation</span></h2>
<div class="opener"><table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">The Hague, 3 April 1783</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>We know by letters from Hamburg of 25 March that your son, after staying there for some days, departed on the 23d.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>Here are some American letters that came via the post from England. The one from Mr. Guild was in a very tattered parcel, open along one side. It contained two pamphlets: <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Letter to the Abb Raynal by Thomas Paine</span>, and <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Catalogus eorum qui in Universitate Harvardiana Cantabrigi in Rep. Massachsi. Ab anno 1642 ad an. 1782 alicujus gradus laurea donati sunt.</span><a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> I thought I should place these two pieces in your writing desk, and send only the letter.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0003" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>A certain face you would not meet in a wood, you will meet it, with his influenza in the future Congress of final pacification, at which I am assured he is appointed to assist. I Sat next him yesterday at the F. Ambassadors, who gave a Diplomatic Dinner.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0004" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> We were much talkative together about the several climates of Russia nearly corresponding with those of our States, and the extensiveness of both, about Kamtschatka, Capt. Cook, the Caspian Sea and Mount Caucase, which he told me he went through. There, said I, you may possibly have traaden on some of the Steps of Alexander the great. He Smiled, and I too, fancying him horded, when there, with the modern Hircanians, so formidable to Caravans.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0005" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0005-ptr">5</a></p>
<p>I am with great respect, your excellencys very humble and very obedient servant</p>
<div class="closer"><p class="signed">Dumas</p>
</div>
</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0385">[385<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0385.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-sn">
   <p><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr> (<span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers</span>); internal address: Paris  Son Excellence Mr. Adams M. P.</p>
</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0001">1</a>
   <p>In fact, <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Quincy Adams (17671848), son of John and Abigail Adams ]">JQA</abbr> left Hamburg on 5 April (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Diary of John Quincy Adams&lt;/i&gt;, ed. David Grayson Allen, Robert J. Taylor, and others, Cambridge, 1981. ]">JQA, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diary</span></span>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-03-01-02-0005-0002-0021%20ADMS-print-03-01-02-0005-0003-0001%20ADMS-print-03-01-02-0005-0004-0001%20ADMS-print-03-01-02-0005-0005-0001#ADMS-03-01-02-pb-0174" class="pageNo">1:174</a>).</p>
</div>
        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0002-ptr" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0002">2</a>
   <p>For the publications sent by Guild, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-14-02-0052" class="document">his letter of 28 Nov. 1782</a>, and note 7, above, but Dumas is probably here referring to <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-14-02-0062" class="document">Guilds letter of 3 Dec.</a>, above, and the cover letter for the pamphlets dated the 7th (<span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers</span>), for which see <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-14-02-0245" class="document"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>s letter to Guild of 9 April</a>, and note 1, below.</p>
</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0003-ptr" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0003">3</a>
   <p>Dumas wrote the following paragraph in English and it has been inserted verbatim into the English translation.</p>
</div>
        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0004-ptr" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0004">4</a>
   <p>Dumas conversation at the French ambassadors dinner was with Arkady Markov, special Russian envoy to the Netherlands. In the summer of 1782 <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> had a humorous exchange with the Russian centering on the similarity between the words influenza and influence (vol. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-13-02-0176#ADMS-06-13-02-pb-0422" class="pageNo">13:422</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-13-02-0176#ADMS-06-13-02-pb-0424" class="pageNo">424425</a>). In March, Catherine II had renewed the Austro-Russian mediation proposal, with the negotiations for the general peace to be held at Paris rather than, as previously intended, at Vienna. Markov was to join the Russian minister to France, Ivan Sergeevich Bariatinskii, for the negotiations (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Isabel de Madariaga, &lt;i&gt;Britain, Russia, and the Armed Neutrality of 1780: Sir James Harris's Mission to St. Petersburg during the American Revolution&lt;/i&gt;, New Haven, 1962. ]">De Madariaga, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Armed Neutrality of 1780</span></span>, p. 433; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The United States and Russia: The Beginning of Relations, 17651815&lt;/i&gt;, ed. Nina N. Bashkina and others, Washington, 1980. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">U.S. and Russia</span></span>, p. 183).</p>
</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0005-ptr" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0242-fn-0005">5</a>
   <p>The Hyrcanians were the inhabitants of a region of ancient Persia located southeast of the Caspian Sea.</p>
</div>
</div>
